The individual finds - analyzes health plans - payor websites for billing related information - enters selected information using a st-ardized data collection system - is responsible for setting up the website tracking - maintenance of the system that auto-tags relevant information contained in the content.  The individual assures for each organization targeted that all are found - any relevant URLs - content are  are collected.

Setup website tracking using “point & click” tools allowing for changes of websites - be identified.

Must be able - analyze overall system set-up concept - successfully resolve over/under tagging issues as they arise
Primary Duties/Responsibility 4:  Curate Internal Notification & Bulletins

Primary Duties/Responsibility 5:  Platform Migration

The ability - take on projects while maintaining current work-load; verbalizing the need for assistance when/if needed.
The Payer Content Intelligence Analyst individual requires the ability - read - identify changes that need - be made - existing Claims Edits - Prior Auth policies as well as create internal bulletins based on their interpretation of the content. While the majority of the content is notifying internal teams of the website or subscription changes the written communication needs - be concise - accurate when documenting policy changes.
Preferred Qualification/s:
The ideal c-idate is experienced in healthcare billing  with knowledge of managed care/payor/healthcare insurance companies who underst-s - has worked with medical policies prior authorization or utilization review.  Ability - comprehensively search the internet for payor content - accurate transcribe data - a prepared template is required. Kaitohutohu Mātāmua Ako/Whanaketanga
Kia ūkaipō anō te reo Māori:
Koinei te tūrua pō o te rautaki reo Māori hou e kīia nei ko Te Maihi Māori he mea waihanga e ngāi Māori mā ngā kāinga ngā hapori me ngā iwi.
I te tīmatanga o te tau 2017 i hui tahi Te Mātāwai me ngā rōpū whai pānga huri noa i te motu ki te kohi haere i ngā kōrero mō ngā kaupapa reo Māori kei ngā kāinga ngā hapori; ngā wawata kei a rātou e pā ana ki te reo Māori tae noa ki ngā mahi a Te Mātāwai hei whakatutuki i ēnei wawata. Nā runga i ēnei kohinga kōrero i hua mai ai Maihi Māori 2017-2040.
Te tūranga mahi:
Kua ara mai he āheinga pārekareka rawa atu mō tētahi Kaitohutohu Mātāmua Ako/Whanaketanga taiea kia mahi i tēnei wāhi mahi whakahirahira mō tētahi tūranga pūmau tekau mā rua marama te roa. He hunga ngākau nui kei Te Mātāwai e kaha pupuri ana i te mana me te whakarauoratanga o te reo Māori.

Research Assistant (CML)
Job Description
The Centre for Maritime Law (CML) at the Faculty of Law National University of Singapore was launched on 3 September 2015 - focuses broadly on international trade transport - shipping law-related issues. It undertakes research - hosts events of scholarly value - academics professionals - government institutions. Its objective is - enhance the development of commercial maritime law in Singapore the region - further afield. CML's continuing achievements include a highly-regarded Working Paper Series (WPS) available at https://law.nus.edu.sg/cml/publications/ [link removed] - the CML CMI Database Judicial Decisions on International Conventions available at https://cmlcmidatabase.org/. [link removed]
The Director of CML is Professor Stephen Girvin MPA Professor of Maritime Law - the Deputy Director is Associate Professor Paul Myburgh.
CML is inviting applications from suitable c-idate(s) who are at the beginning of their professional careers - conduct research - participate in CML's work. Depending on qualifications background - expertise the successful applicant(s) will be appointed as a Research Assistant in CML.
The successful applicant will join CML's existing full-time - Adjunct research staff (see https://law.nus.edu.sg/cml/personnel/ [link removed]).
Benefits
The position(s) will carry the following benefits:
1. Employment on a full-time contract at NUS Law for one year - subject - satisfactory performance may be renewable for a second year.
2. A compensation package commensurate with qualifications - experience.
3. Allocation of designated workspace within CML.
Duties
The duties associated with the position(s) are as follows:
1. The successful applicant will be expected - be in residence throughout the term of his or her appointment subject - the normal NUS terms as - annual leave.
2. Depending on experience the successful applicant will be expected - develop his or her own research agenda including undertaking research projects on maritime law leading - publication in English-language refereed journals during his or her term of appointment. The proposed research agenda MUST also include writing working papers for publication in the CML Working Paper Series (https://law.nus.edu.sg/cml/publications/ [link removed]).
3. The successful applicant will also be required - present his or her research - - participate in - contribute - CML seminars.
4. The successful applicant is expected - assist in CML's research projects - initiatives including the CML CMI Database Judicial Decisions on International Conventions (https://www.cmlcmidatabase.org/).
5. The successful applicant may be asked - act as research assistant - the Director or Deputy Director of CML as assigned by the Director of CML.
Qualifications
Requirements
The selection committee will consider the following criteria in making an appointment for the position of Research Assistant in CML:
1. The successful applicant will be of exceptional calibre.
2. For appointment as a Research Assistant the successful applicant must have an Honours degree (or equivalent) in law preferably with a postgraduate degree in maritime law (or an interest in pursuing such a degree) or demonstrate a strong interest in maritime law.
3. Applications are invited from those with interests in any branch of commercial maritime or shipping law or admiralty law or marine insurance law including the international sale of goods carried by sea maritime conflict of laws maritime dispute resolution (including maritime arbitration especially in the Asian context) - offshore oil - gas law. A demonstrated interest in contemporary research on maritime law such as the impact of COVID-19 on the maritime sector ship finance in the 21st century - decarbonisation - the shipping industry may be an advantage.
4. Applications are not sought from those with primary interests in the international law of the sea ocean law - policy or international environmental law.

- Application form HERE [link removed]

A detailed curriculum vita should be submitted containing complete - detailed information on academic institutions honours awards all publications - date - all professional experience (current - previous including dates of employment - job descriptions).
4. Letters of Recommendation
The application must be supported by two references from academic referees. Applicants must arrange for their referees - send their references - the address below by the closing date.
5. Submission of Application Materials
Interested applicants are invited - apply - submit their applications directly at our NUS Career Portal.
6. Closing Date

如就工資期須支付予僱員的工資少於最低工資，僱員有權就該工資期獲付這差額（即「額外報酬」）。該僱員的僱傭合約須視為他有權就該工資期獲得額外報酬，而該額外報酬亦適用於計算根據其他相關法例所應獲得的款項。

Me ngātahi te mahi i runga i te wairua whakahoahoa e hua ake ai ngā hononga whai pānga kia rata mai ai hoki ētahi atu. Ko tō māia ki te tautohu i ngā āheinga tautīnei i Te Mātāwai mā roto i ngā toronga maha tētahi mahi nui i tēnei tūranga mahi. Senior Urban Designer
Me Heke Ki Pōneke
-
Wellington City Council has declared an ecological - climate emergency as it adopts a blueprint for becoming a zero-carbon city - Our City Tomorrow. It's an exciting time - join our team of city shapers - play a key role in transforming how people live work play - travel across the city!
Kia mahi ngātahi mō Pōneke mō tōna āpōpō
Working together for Wellington's future.
People love living in Te Whanganui-a-Tara Wellington. We are a vibrant connected - compact city that frequently tops global city quality-of-life surveys. So it's no wonder more people want - live here. By 2050 we're expecting 500000 - 80000 more Wellingtonians - 25% more people coming into the central city each workday from across the region.
- ensure our city continues - thrive as a healthy safe - sustainable creative capital where people live work - play we have committed - delivering an ambitious exciting Long-term Plan. This Plan includes a number of key strategies that put people - innovation at the heart of how we design - deliver a more creative prosperous - greener capital. Our Planning - Environment group is leading many of these strategies from delivering more affordable housing installing new bike networks - helping our capital become a net zero-carbon city by 2050.
This role sits within the Urban Regeneration - Design team (within the City Design unit in the Planning & Environment Group) that will work across the City Design unit the organisation - in collaboration with the community - private sector - embrace initiative - influence positive city outcomes in private development.
The Senior Urban Designer will contribute - the Design Review workstream (the gateway - all public - private developments) champion a 'design led' approach - undertake timely urban design assessment technical review - evaluation of development proposals. Additionally this role involves a unique opportunity - contribute - establishing a Design Review Programme - associated Design Review Panels. The role's contributions - various aspects of the Design Review Team interrelate - help ensure that Wellington's future growth meets the ambitious goals of Our City Tomorrow - that all new development (whether public or private) is held - best-practice urban design st-ards.
Although detailed knowledge of the Resource Management Act ($A) is not necessary the successful applicant should underst- how the District Plan assists Council in achieving the best practice urban design outcomes - sustainable management goals. Our ideal person will have a relevant degree in urban design related field such as l-scape architecture architecture planning or related. 5+ years of experience in architectural practices or other relevant construction industries would be an advantage.
This is a collaborative role which involves close working relationships with a diverse group of stakeholders especially in a complex political environment with your strong influencing skills you will be able - get alongside the stakeholders underst- their imperatives - look for the win-win. You will be calm headed - resilient with the ability - listen empathise - form awesome relationships in a high-pressure environment.
More importantly you will be an awesome team player who gets excited about the public life of cities - committed - making a difference by creating Wellington as an Urban Village with a Wild Edge. Council values - celebrates the uniquely compact - vibrant qualities of Wellington - is committed - best practice built - natural environment outcomes. Naturally we think our council is the best - we offer range of benefits that includes flexible working model 5 weeks annual leave after 2 years of continuous service for permanent staff - much more!
If this opportunity excites you then we would welcome your application!
All applications for this role must be submitted online - will be treated in strict confidence. If you would like more information or have a confidential chat before applying you are welcome - contact Farzad Zamani Manager Urban Regeneration & Design at farzad.zamani@wcc.govt.nz. Applicants must be legally eligible - work in New Zeal- or must be in the process of obtaining a visa with a set date - come - NZ.
Applications will close
10 April 2022.

Our Vaccination Policy covers this role which means COVID-19 vaccinations are m-atory.
If successful it will be a requirement of your employment that you are fully vaccinated - that you provide your personal vaccine pass as an official record of your COVID-19 vaccination status.

Conseillers Principaux Projets d'énergie renouvelable
Excellente opportunité de rejoindre l'équipe des Projets d'énergie renouvelable
Poste basé à Perth Brisbane ou Montréal
Nouveaux postes de base dans le domaine des énergies renouvelables où votre expertise peut briller
À propos du rôle
Rio Tinto a récemment créé une équipe dédiée pour fournir des solutions d'énergie renouvelable dans nos principales juridictions. Rio Tinto Energy Development (RTED) se concentre sur l'accélération du développement des actifs énergétiques futurs et sur la garantie d'une option de développement d'énergie renouvelable de haute qualité. L'accent mis par l'équipe sur la fourniture d'énergie verte permettra la décarbonisation des opérations industrielles existantes de l'entreprise et soutiendra la croissance future de Rio Tinto.
RTED comprend une équipe de projets d'énergie renouvelable centralisée qui travaillera avec les actifs en dehors de nos principales régions énergétiques où nous considérons les énergies renouvelables à la fois comme un levier de réduction et une fonction de croissance future pour l'avenir (Québec Pacifique et Pilbara). Ces actifs en dehors des régions centrales ont devant eux des solutions d'énergie renouvelable détaillées et complexes et comprennent à la fois des actifs de croissance existants et nouveaux. L'équipe se consacre à soutenir les résultats de la réduction des énergies renouvelables et aidera les groupes de produits à prendre des mesures pour permettre une adoption et une exécution plus rapides des solutions d'énergie renouvelable. Il est important de noter que l'équipe est plus qu'un service de conseil et se tiendra aux côtés des Groupes de produits lorsque des décisions seront prises sur les opportunités renouvelables.
Pour renforcer cela nous recherchons des conseillers principaux dans l'équipe des projets d'énergie renouvelable. Ces postes-clés peuvent être basés à Perth Brisbane ou Montréal.
Les c-idats que nous recherchons auront une expérience récente et prouvée dans la livraison de projets renouvelables la création d'accords sur les énergies renouvelables et/ou la construction d'énergies renouvelables. Vous travaillerez aux côtés des équipes de site existantes apportant une expertise approfondie aux négociations externes ou au développement d'actifs renouvelables internes et tirerez parti de votre compréhension des limites de pénétration des énergies renouvelables.
Vous travaillerez en partenariat avec l'entreprise sur l'analyse des options (quantitatives et qualitatives) et démontrerez votre capacité d'exécution pour soutenir la livraison du projet et l'optionnalité à long terme.
Grâce à vos compétences d'influence interpersonnelles et relationnelles votre analyse et vos présentations feront partie intégrante de la création de solutions axées sur le commerce et de la communication efficace avec les principaux intervenants. Votre rôle jouera un rôle-clé dans l'obtention des meilleurs résultats renouvelables dans l'ensemble de nos actifs et dans la création d'une culture gagnante pour faire la différence.
L'intention de ces rôles est de livrer aux côtés des Groupes de produits et le c-idat retenu préparera et mènera des discussions avec le Groupe plus large sur les opportunités de réduction.
C'est un excellent moment pour rejoindre la compagnie dans des rôles clés définir l'agenda et produire des résultats. Les personnes qui peuvent penser agir et réussir tout en conduisant le changement en fournissant une orientation et en répondant aux besoins de l'entreprise pourront commencer ici et aller n'importe où.
Nous avons des opportunités en tant que Conseillers Principal- Commercial et Conseiller Principal – Technique.

如你有合理懷疑僱主未有遵守《僱傭條例》、《僱員補償條例》、《最低工資條例》，可致電熱線2717 1771（由1823接聽）或電郵-enquiry@labour.gov.hk 查詢。-於涉及《性別歧視條例》、《殘疾歧視條例》、《家庭崗位歧視條例》或《種族歧視條例》的查詢，請聯絡平等機會委員會。
根據《最低工資條例》的規定，僱主須就任何工資期，確保支付僱員不少於按下列方法計算的
最低工資
：
最低工資=僱員於工資期的總工作時數 x 法定最低工資水平（即每小時40元1）
1由2023年5月1日起，法定最低工資水平已調升-每小時40元。
如就工資期須支付予僱員的工資少於最低工資，僱員有權就該工資期獲付這差額（即「額外報酬」）。該僱員的僱傭合約須視為他有權就該工資期獲得額外報酬，而該額外報酬亦適用於計算根據其他相關法例所應獲得的款項。
有關法定最低工資的定義及計算詳情，請瀏覽 《法定最低工資：僱主及僱員參考指引》或致電 24 小時查詢熱線 2717 1771（由「1823」接聽）。

如就工資期須支付予僱員的工資少於最低工資，僱員有權就該工資期獲付這差額（即「額外報酬」）。該僱員的僱傭合約須視為他有權就該工資期獲得額外報酬，而該額外報酬亦適用於計算根據其他相關法例所應獲得的款項。
有關法定最低工資的定義及計算詳情，請瀏覽 《法定最低工資：僱主及僱員參考指引》或致電 24 小時查詢熱線 2717 1771（由「1823」接聽）。

The Training Program
Each anaesthetic Trainee is one of 5 Trainees.
Three are non-rotational - may be on the independent scheme - two rotates 6-monthly from Westmead. There will be three extra residents rotating from other specialties. The Trainees report - the supervising anaesthetist of the day in-hours - the on-call anaesthetist out of hours. They participate in departmental meetings - clinical review present papers - talks at departmental meetings attend tutorials - seminars - are subject - regular assessment - guidance by senior members of the department.
Trainees are further assessed for satisfactory progress by the supervisor of training. The rotational Trainees are given assessments which are returned - their departments at Westmead. The Head of Department Supervisor of Training - WBA Assessors are approved by the ANZ College of Anaesthetists in those positions.
Selection Criteria:
MBBS or equivalent currently registered with the Medical Board of Australia
Minimum 3 years of post-graduate experience with at least 2 years in Australia
Good oral - written communication skills
Recent Australian experience in anaesthetics critical care HDU or ICU
Competence in cannulation compensation airway management interpretation of blood - blood gas results. compensation life support skills expected. Advanced life support skills - EMST attendance advantageous
Ability - participate in a 1 in 5 out of hours “on call” roster involving nights - weekends. Must live within 20-30 minutes of hospital.
Registration or intended registration with ANZ College of Anaesthetists as a compensation Trainee.
Research or clinical governance activity or interest.

What you'll be doing
The vision for South Eastern Sydney Local Health District (SESLHD) is ‘exceptional care healthier lives’. SESLHD is committed - enabling our community - be healthy - well - - providing the best possible compassionate care when people need it.
This role will provide leadership - management for a team delivering clinical pharmacy services in a defined practice area across SESLHD. The position will be a district-wide role working across the SESLHD sites providing services with flexible hours across the seven day week participating in after hours weekend - public holiday work. The position will be shared with another Team Leader - maintain leadership - management of a team across the seven day week. It will be required - undertake clinical duties as well as provide leadership including support - line management of pharmacy staff. The role will collaborate with the SESLHD Pharmacy Leadership Team Quality Use of Medicines Lead Pharmacist Senior Pharmacists - all SESLHD Pharmacy departments - ensure consistent - effective service provision across SESLHD.
Employment of a temporary visa holder may only occur if no suitable permanent resident or citizen of Australia has been identified for this position following suitable labour market testing.

Acceptable proof of vaccination is the Australian Immunisation Register (AIR) Immunisation History Statement or AIR COVID-19 Digital Certificate. Booster doses are highly recommended for all health care workers who have completed the primary course of COVID-19 vaccinations.

Research Fellow (Mechanobiology Institute)
Job Description
The Mechanobiology Institute Singapore is a multi-disciplinary institute committed - develop new paradigms for biomedical research by focusing on the quantitative analysis of dynamic functional processes. Through quantitative biophysical approaches we address major problems in biomedical sciences including pathogenesis (from bacterial - cancer) tissue regeneration - function.
Asst. Prof. Chan is seeking a highly motivated individual - join my laboratory on Mammalian Development - Tissue Hydraulics at the Mechanobiology Institute in the National University of Singapore. My laboratory seeks - underst- the mechanobiology principles underlying ovarian follicle development using ex vivo mouse ovary - follicle culture.
The c-idate will have a chance - apply - develop interdisciplinary approaches - investigate how tissue stress - fluid pressure control follicle growth. The c-idate will combine quantitative imaging with biomimetic approaches established in the lab - characterize the cellular dynamics - fluid lumen formation during follicle development. He/she will also apply biophysical - molecular perturbations - dissect the molecular mechanisms regulating these processes - collaborate with theoreticians - develop biophysical models. He/she will be expected - participate in ongoing collaborations with researchers in Japan - Europe.
Qualifications
C-idates with a PhD in biophysics engineering cell - developmental biology are encouraged - apply. They should have a strong background in confocal - 2-photon imaging image analysis - some research experiences in tissue biology -/or mechanobiology. Prior knowledge of the mouse model is not a prerequisite. The c-idate should possess excellent communication skills - engage in collaborative research in a highly interdisciplinary environment.

Kaiwhakahaere Haumitanga mō Te Reo Māori
Kia ūkaipō anō te reo Māori:
Koinei te tūrua pō o te rautaki reo Māori hou e kīia nei ko Te Maihi Māori he mea waihanga e ngāi Māori mō ngā kāinga ngā hapori me ngā iwi.
I te tīmatanga o te tau 2017 i hui tahi Te Mātāwai me ngā rōpū whai pānga huri noa i te motu ki te kohi haere i ngā kōrero mō ngā kaupapa reo Māori kei ngā kāinga ngā hapori; ngā wawata kei a rātou e pā ana ki te reo Māori tae noa ki ngā mahi a Te Mātāwai ki te whakatutuki i ēnei wawata. Nā runga i ēnei kohinga kōrero i hua mai ai Te Maihi Māori 2017-2040.
Te tūranga:
Kei tēnei tūranga hiamo inā rā mā tō noho hei mema ki tēnei rōpū whakahaere kei a koe te haepapa ki te ārahi me te whakahaere i ngā tukanga rautaki haumitanga whakawhiwhinga hoki me te waihanga hoki i ētahi pou tarāwaho auaha e pā ana ki ngā mahi whakataunga ā-kāhui me ngā mahi whakamahere reo. Mātua rā ko tāu mahi he whakahaere i te rōpū he tuku tohutohu he ārahi hoki i te hunga whai pānga me ngā kaiārahi. Ko tāu mahi hoki he whakarite he whakahaere i te hōtaka mahi arā ko te whakahaere i ngā kirimana te tiaki i ngā pūrongo me te arotakenga o ngā mahere haumitanga.
He kōrero mōu ake:
E angitū ai koe ki tēnei tūranga hei mema ki te rōpū whakahaere me whai koe te kaitono:
Te hiranga o ōu pūkenga whakamōhiohio tō matatau ki te kōrero i te reo Māori tae noa ki tō mārama ki ngā tikanga me ngā mātāpono o Te Tiriti o Waitangi;
Ōu wheako ki ngā mahi whakahaere tahua haumitanga me ngā whakawhiwhinga ki ngā kaupapa kei ngā kāinga ngā hapori me ngā iwi;
He huatau mahi ngātahi i runga i ngā pūkenga tohutohu ārahi arataki hoki i te hunga whai pānga i ā rātou tukanga whakatau kaupapa;
Ōu pūkenga tātari wetewete hoki i ngā raruraru tō ngākau pono me tō taunga ki ngā whakahaerenga tūraru e kitea ai tō māia ki te whakamahi i ēnei momo pūkenga kia whai hua ai ngā whakataunga i ngā wā taumaha;
Tō ngākau nui mō te whakarauoratanga o te reo Māori me ōu wheako mō te mahi tahi atu ki ngā whānau ngā hapū ngā iwi ngā wāhi mahi Māori me ngā hapori Māori hoki.
